[[Image:Lundy inscribed stones.jpg|thumb|Inscribed Stones]]
'''Celtic inscribed stones''' are stone monuments dating from 400 to 1000 AD. They are inscribed with [[Celtic languages|Celtic]] or [[Latin]] text, which can be written in [[Ogham inscription|Ogham]] or [[Latin script|Roman]] letters. Some stones have both Ogham and Roman inscriptions. The stones are found in [[Ireland]], [[Scotland]], [[Wales]], [[Brittany]], the [[Isle of Man]], and parts of western [[England]] (mainly [[Cornwall]], [[Devon]], and [[Lundy]]).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/archaeology/cisp/database/ |title=Celtic Inscribed Stones Project history |accessdate=2008-01-08 |format= |work= }}</ref>

They relate to other standing stones with decoration, such as the [[Turoe Stone]] and [[Castlestrange Stone]]. 

