{{Infobox artwork | image_file = Waterhouse, JW - The Sorceress (1913).jpg | title = The Sorceress | artist = [[John William Waterhouse]] | year = c. 1911 | medium = [[Oil painting|Oil on canvas]] | material = | height_metric = 76 | width_metric = 110.5 | metric_unit = cm<!--don't leave this parameter blank—either don't include it, or include the default cm. Not including it will default it to cm.--> | city = | museum = | owner = }}
'''''The Sorceress''''' is a painting by [[John William Waterhouse]] completed between 1911 and 1915.<ref name="Hobson">Hobson, Anthony. 1989. ''J. W. Waterhouse''. Oxford: Phaidon Christie's. pages 77, 89, 101-105. {{ISBN|0-7148-8066-3}}</ref><ref name="leicester">{{cite web|url=http://www.leicestergalleries.com/19th-20th-century-paintings/d/circe--the-sorceress/13926|title=Circe (The Sorceress)|publisher=The Leicester Galleries|accessdate=30 January 2013}}</ref> It is his third depiction, after ''[[Circe Offering the Cup to Ulysses]]'' (1891) and ''[[Circe Invidiosa]]'' (1892), of the Greek mythological character, [[Circe]], and her name is on the back of the canvas.<ref name="Hobson" /> The inclusion of [[leopards]] and the [[loom]] offer further evidence that the painting is of Circe.<ref name="leicester" />
An oil study for ''The Sorceress'' (c. 1911, 61x51cm, in a private collection) shows a model with dark brown hair. For the final scene, Circe is depicted as a redhead.<ref name="Hobson" />
